Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: Centum Investment, Co-Operative Bank Are Active

-- B y   R o b e r t   B r a n d
-- 
2011-06-07T15:54:39Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-07/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-centum-investment-co-operative-bank.html
Kenya ’s All-Share Index rose to its
highest level in more than a week, gaining 0.2 percent to 73.75
by the 3 p.m. close in Nairobi.  The Ghana Stock Exchange Composite Index climbed for a
seventh day, adding less than 0.1 percent to 1,169.55 by the 3
p.m. close in Accra, bringing its advance in the seven-day
period to 0.6 percent. Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index advanced 0.2
percent to 2,081.41 by the 1:30 p.m. close in  Port Louis .
Namibia’s FTSE/ Namibia Overall Index (FTN098)  rose 0.5 percent to 850.44
at the 4 p.m. close in Windhoek, and the Nigerian Stock Exchange
All-Share Index dropped for a third day, losing 0.3 percent to
25,741.94 by the 2:30 p.m. close in Lagos.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Centum Investment Co. (CENTUM KN) gained the most in more
than two weeks after the Nairobi-based company said it plans to
invest in geothermal projects in Kenya. The shares added 75
cents, or 3.3 percent, to 23.5 shillings.  Co-Operative Bank of Kenya Ltd. (COOP)  , the East African
nation’s fourth-biggest lender by assets, retreated 5 cents, or
0.3 percent, to 17.25 shillings, a two-month low, on concern the
cost of cutting 34 senior managerial jobs will hurt earnings.  CMC Holdings Ltd. (CMCH)  , a Kenyan car dealer, rose 5
cents, or 0.4 percent, to 13 shillings, a six-month high, after
the company said it plans to spend as much as 1 billion
shillings ($11.4 million) to expand its operations.  To contact the reporter on this story:
